S	SH10	PMID:30768760	The small genomes of cultivated Nanoarchaeota lack nearly all biosynthetic pathways and have split protein-coding genes (Waters et al., 2003; Wurch et al., 2016; St. John et al., 2019), pointing to a common pattern of genomic reduction and fragmentation.
S	SH12	PMID:30768760	Unlike cultivated Nanoarchaeota, however, the Gua-46 MAG contains a predicted tyrosine-specific transporter (Gua_114), which may allow the nanoarchaeote to uptake this amino acid from the environment. The MC-1 MAG also encodes for genes involved in nucleotide biotransformation that have not been previously identified in cultivated nanoarchaeotes, including a cytidylate kinase (MC-1_488) and a uridylate kinase (MC-1_320).
S	SH14	PMID:30768760	However, MC-1 does encode genes involved in the pentose bisphosphate pathway, previously described in Thermococcus kodakarensis (Fig. 4), which would allow nanoarchaeotal cells to produce 3-phosphoglycerate and bypass the missing steps in glycolysis (Aono et al., 2012; 2015). The pentose bisphosphate pathway typically begins with nucleoside monophosphates, which may be produced by a putative nucleoside kinase (MC_288) that shows 35.1%–37.4% amino acid similarity to nucleoside kinases in Methanocaldococcus jannaschii and Aeropyrum pernix (Hansen et al., 2007; Aono et al., 2015).
